# Episode 2 — Node 01 — Watch Incoming Email

## Node Info
```
Node Type : Gmail Trigger
Node Name : 01 - Watch Incoming Email
What it does: Watches the Gmail inbox every 1 minute
              Fires the workflow when a new email arrives
```

## How I Built It
```
Click "+" on the canvas
Search: Gmail
Under Triggers section → select: On message received ⚡
Rename: 01 - Watch Incoming Email
```

## Config Settings
```
Credential : My Gmail account
Event      : Message Received
Simplify   : ON
Poll Times : Every 1 Minute
```

## How I Tested It
```
Clicked Fetch Test Event
Gmail pulled in the most recent email
Data appeared in the output ✅
```

## Why I Built It This Way
This node is always watching.
Even when I am asleep it checks every minute.
The moment an email lands, the whole workflow fires.
I used Fetch Test Event instead of sending a new email
because it is faster and does not waste executions.

## What the Output Contains
```
id           → Gmail message ID
threadId     → Email thread ID
snippet      → Preview text of the email
subject      → Email subject line
from         → Sender information
internalDate → When the email was received
labels       → Gmail labels on the email
```

---

---

# Episode 3 — Node 02 — Extract Email Data

## Node Info
```
Node Type : Edit Fields (Set)
Node Name : 02 - Extract Email Data
What it does: Pulls sender name, sender email,
              subject, and body into clean short fields
```

## How I Built It
```
Click "+" after Node 01
Search: Edit Fields
Select it
Rename: 02 - Extract Email Data
Mode: Manual Mapping
```

## The 4 Fields I Set Up

```
Field 1
Name : sender_email
Type : String
Value: {{ $json.from.value[0].address }}

Field 2
Name : sender_name
Type : String
Value: {{ $json.from.value[0].name }}

Field 3
Name : subject
Type : String
Value: {{ $json.subject }}

Field 4
Name : body
Type : String
Value: {{ $json.snippet }}
```

## What the Output Looked Like
```
sender_email: "mostakinhossain0@gmail.com"
sender_name : "mostakin hossain"
subject     : "hello"
body        : "i can buy food"
```

## Why I Built It This Way
Gmail sends data in a nested structure.
Writing $json.from.value[0].address every time is painful.
I extract it once here and give it clean short names.
Every node after this uses sender_email, sender_name, subject, body.
Simple and clean.

## Important Note About Body
```
$json.text sometimes comes back empty.
Use $json.snippet instead.
snippet is Gmail's preview text — always available.
It gives enough context for AI to write a good reply.
```

---

---

# Episode 4 — Node 03 — AI Read and Reply

## Node Info
```
Node Type : OpenAI
Node Name : 03 - AI Read and Reply
Model     : GPT-4o-mini
Operation : Message a Model
What it does: Reads the email content and writes
              a professional reply automatically
```

## How I Built It
```
Click "+" after Node 02
Search: OpenAI
Select it
Rename: 03 - AI Read and Reply
Credential: OpenAI API Key
Resource: Text
Operation: Message a Model
Model: GPT-4o-mini
```

## System Prompt I Used
```
You are a professional email assistant for a
Digital Marketing Agency.

Your job is to read incoming emails and write
a professional, warm, and helpful reply.

RULES:
- Always greet the sender by their first name
- Keep the reply short and clear
- Sound human — not robotic
- Always end with a call to action
- Sign off as: "Best regards, Sarah — Digital Marketing Team"

TYPES OF EMAILS YOU WILL HANDLE:

1. PRICING QUESTION
If they ask about price or cost, reply with:
Our packages start from $500/month.
We offer Social Media, Google Ads, and SEO packages.
Book a free call to get a custom quote.

2. SERVICE INQUIRY
If they ask what services we offer, reply with:
We offer Social Media Marketing, Google Ads,
Facebook Ads, SEO, and Email Automation.
Each package is customized to your business needs.

3. MEETING REQUEST
If they want to book a call or meeting, reply with:
We would love to connect!
Book a free 30-minute call here: [calendar-link]
We are available Monday to Friday, 9am to 6pm.

4. GENERAL EMAIL
If it does not fit the above, write a warm
professional reply that makes sense for the email.

RESPONSE FORMAT:
Return ONLY a valid JSON object. Nothing else.

{
  "reply": "<your full email reply here>",
  "category": "<Pricing/Service/Meeting/General>"
}
```

## User Message I Used
```
Sender Name : {{ $json.sender_name }}
Sender Email: {{ $json.sender_email }}
Subject     : {{ $json.subject }}
Email Body  : {{ $json.body }}

Write a professional reply to this email.
```

## What the Output Looked Like
```
{
  "reply"   : "Hi Mostakin, Thank you for reaching out...",
  "category": "General"
}
```

## Why I Built It This Way
I gave AI 4 types of emails with exact reply templates.
This keeps replies consistent and on-brand every time.
Return ONLY JSON means no extra text that breaks parsing.
The category field lets me track what kind of emails come in.
A client can filter the Sheet by category to see patterns.
This is a real business intelligence feature — not just automation.

---

---

# Episode 5 — Node 04 — Parse AI Response

## Node Info
```
Node Type : Code Node
Node Name : 04 - Parse AI Response
Language  : JavaScript
Mode      : Run Once for All Items
What it does: Extracts reply and category from AI text
              Combines everything into one clean output
```

## How I Built It
```
Click "+" after Node 03
Search: Code
Select it
Rename: 04 - Parse AI Response
Language: JavaScript
Mode: Run Once for All Items
```

## Full Code
```javascript
const items = $input.all();
const results = [];

for (const item of items) {

  // Get AI response text
  // n8n 2026 OpenAI response path
  const rawText = item.json.output[0].content[0].text;

  // Parse JSON string into real object
  const parsed = JSON.parse(rawText);

  // Combine Node 02 data + AI output into one clean object
  results.push({
    json: {
      sender_email: $('02 - Extract Email Data').item.json.sender_email,
      sender_name : $('02 - Extract Email Data').item.json.sender_name,
      subject     : $('02 - Extract Email Data').item.json.subject,
      body        : $('02 - Extract Email Data').item.json.body,
      reply       : parsed.reply,
      category    : parsed.category
    }
  });
}

return results;
```

## What the Output Looked Like
```
sender_email: "mostakinhossain0@gmail.com"
sender_name : "mostakin hossain"
subject     : "hello"
body        : "i can buy food"
reply       : "Hi Mostakin, Thank you for reaching out..."
category    : "General"
```

## Why I Built It This Way
AI returns plain text — cannot use it directly.
I parse it into a real object and pull out reply and category.
I combine Node 02 data here so the next nodes have everything.
One clean output. No jumping between nodes for data.
Same pattern I used in Workflow 9 — once you know it, use it everywhere.

## Critical Things That Must Be Right
```
OpenAI response path in n8n 2026:
output[0].content[0].text ✅

Old format that no longer works:
message.content ❌

Must reference Node 02 by name after any branching:
$('02 - Extract Email Data').item.json.sender_email ✅
$json.sender_email ❌
```

